*INSTALL KIND CLUSTER IN YOUR LOCAL SYSTEM TO PRACTICE***
CKA first set of learning.
QUESTION-1
update your image nginx with 1.20 as its 1.19?
kubctl get deployment -o wide
required file deployment.yaml
image-name=nginx-pod
deployment name=new
command will use: kubectl set image deployment new nginx-pod=1.20

QUESTION-2
how to change path 0f the static pod?
requirments: learn first what are static pods and what are their usecases
1st step: need to identify path of the static pod to change the path
ps -aux | grep "kubelet"

static pods maintained by kubelet not by control manager
get into kubelet config file path
nano or vi it
you will get STATIC POD PATH=etc/kubernetes/manifests
change and save.

QUESTION-3
upgrade the cluster from 1.26 to 1.29
kubeadm = 1.26
kubelet= 1.26
kubectl=1.26

cordon the node
kubectl cordon node-ip

drain the node
kubectl drain node node-ip --dry-run --ignore=deamonsets

sudo apt update
apt install kubeadm=1.29
kubeadm upgrade apply 1.29
apt install kubelet=1.29
apt install kubectl=1.29

systemctl restart kubelet
kubectl uncordon node

QUESTION-4
create pod with lablels from command line?
pod-name:nginx
image:alpine:1.2
label: tier=frontend

command
kubectl run pod nginx image:alpine:1.2 -l tier=frontend
it creates pod and label
kubectl describe pod nginx 
use show labels also

QUESTION-5
create deployment with 3 replicas?
deployment: demo
image: nginx:1.19
command:
kubectl create deployment demo --image=nginx:1.19 --replicas=3
kubectl describe deployment demo

QUSTION-6
create pod with below requirments and expose it to http i mean 8080?
pod-name: nginx-pod
image: nginx:1.20
service-name: pod-service
port: 8080
target-port: 8080

kubectl run nginx-pod --image=nginx:1.20
pod get create
assign service
kubectl expose pod --name=pod-service --port=8080 --target-port=8080
kubectl describe svc pod-service

QUESTION-7
create pod under namspace dev?
pod-name: new
image: nginx:1.20
namspace : dev
command to create namspace
kubectl create namspace dev
dev namspace is created

create a pod under this namspace:
kubectl run new --image=nginx:1.20 -n dev
kubectl get pods -n dev
new (pod is present)

QUESTION-8
 create static pod with command sleep=500?
pod: static-pod
image: httpd

1 step: ps -aux | grep "kubelet"
nano kubelet config file path
find the path like this
static-pod-path: /etc/kubernetes/manifests
now in your root terminal
kubectl run static-pod --image=httpd --command sleep 500 --dry-run=client -o yaml
this above command give you yaml file of pod with all configuration you added 
copy the yaml to  /etc/kubernetes/manifests

once you add file automatically it create pod, not required to apply or execute, thats the beauty of static pods
